text: So at this, I mean, that's an excellent question. And I guess in many ways, it kind of depends on the strategy. I'll give you two examples. But at the simplest level, there's kind of two ways I think about it. At the simplest level, it's if there's another rule, if you're adding a measure or you're adding a rule, if there's another if then or another screen going into place, we think about that as a degree of freedom. So if somebody wants to move away from just looking at price to book as a single measure of value and incorporate something else like price to earnings or price to sales, or probably the inverse, that represents a degree of freedom. Now, I would argue that's a well-spent degree of freedom because you're effectively buying robustness. And this is something you've talked about and really done a good job illustrating is the fragility of single signals. And actually, a good example is when I was at VanEck, we were evaluating an external index provider that had a long flat commodity index. And so it was, if I remember correctly, it was a signal one look back, it was a moving average crossover strategy, where they were looking at the five-day moving average by I believe the 250 moving average applied to the 20 most liquid futures products. Very simple, very robust, the evidence in favor of... So Jan VanEck asked me to take a look at it. And I was like, AQR has written ad nauseum about the utility of momentum, particularly for a volatile asset. And I was like, well, I'm going to take a look at it. And I was like, well, classic commodities, Mark Malick again. I was like, it makes a lot of sense. However, at a minimum, we'd want to understand the risk isn't necessarily... Yes, you're diversifying across instrument. And yes, you're setting up a rule that's effectively designed to truncate that left tail risk. But how do we know that five by 250 is the magic number? And this isn't an optimization exercise, but I want to make sure I didn't inadvertently pick the best iteration of that. And so what I did was go through... And evaluated the Sharpe ratio. I created a 3D plot, really pretty heat map where Sharpe ratio was on the Z-axis. And then the fast moving average was on one Y-axis and the slow moving average was on the other. So you had every combination of zero or call it five to 50 days on the quote unquote fast moving average. And I think we looked at 50 to 250 on the slow moving average. And what we plotted was the Sharpe ratio. And there's a million different ways you can look at this. On the Z-axis, we had a lot of different ways to look at this. And I think we looked at the Sharpe ratio. And then on the Y-axis, we kind of swapped out a bunch of different metrics that we were interested in, but Sharpe ratio is a good example. We plotted this topology. And so it was a really nice heat map. And what you saw and what I kind of wrote for the internal memo is, again, the objective... If we were to run a data mining exercise, we would want to pick the exact tippy top of the global maxima of this topology. We're not in that game. What we do want to do is we want to quantify the degree that there's potentially signal risk of only relying on the Sharpe ratio. This one little point on this Cartesian plane of five-day moving average by 200-day moving average. And it happened to be a little bit lower on the plane. So arguably, you could do better just by simply moving to different specifications. But at a minimum, the point I made was, you probably want to diversify. What we're seeing is that irrespective of what combination you pick, it outperforms simple buy and hold, not just on absolute returns, but risk-adjusted downside risk, all of that. So why not diversify away from that signal, that single signal? And again, I think that's a really good illustration. And I always use it as an example for prospective clients when we go through this exercise of testing all these different iterations because it really... Even for non-quantitatively oriented people, they kind of instantly get... And I just did this exercise for a bigger RA where I actually showed a redacted version of this memo. And they kind of instantly get, okay, I got it. I don't know... I don't necessarily want to try and pick the global maximum, but I also don't want to have my only exposure be this one signal. And so to answer your question a little bit more directly, it's those kinds of exercises where we go through. And like I said, with this other client that had a very complex idea about European dividend value stocks where anytime there's a new rule or a new screen or a new something in the recipe, so to speak, we just want to test kind of every iteration of the equation. And so I think that's a really good illustration of that's reasonable to understand what is the benefit from that additional rule, that additional loss of a degree of freedom. And then also, what is the risk? Did we inadvertently pick a local maximum or did we inadvertently pick the one spot that performs well, but if you shifted even a little bit, everything goes off the rails. And so I would say, ironically, or maybe not, but in the kind of custom indexing or indexing as a service area, I would argue that exercise is probably really the best way to do it. And I think that's a really good example of how you can the value add. It's not that we've got the secret sauce for defining value. It's that our value prop is set up to give the right kind of investor kind of the most comprehensive view of the exposure they're getting and then ultimately build it and deliver it for them.
